:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/3B3A9FD3-3385-4A4D-8DFF-79C37234A106"><gtr:id>3B3A9FD3-3385-4A4D-8DFF-79C37234A106</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Judith</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Good</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-149-25-1064"><gtr:id>0DD8E44C-1CEF-4DAB-967C-3BFA12C0F820</gtr:id><gtr:title>Towards Making GRID-enabled Schools eScience Usable and Reusable for and with Teachers</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-149-25-1064</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project explores the usability issues around putting Grid-enabled e-Science technologies into the hands of teachers and learners. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The key objectives are:&lt;br />&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>To develop new e-Science communities involving science teachers and pupils and in so doing to explore the barriers and usability issues in the design of e-Science systems&amp;nbsp;&lt;br />
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To expose young people to the possibilities of e-Science as a natural way of engaging in scientific research.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br />
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>To increase our understanding of the ways in which new knowledge is formulated and understood within an educational context supported by e-Science technology.&lt;br />&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>A participatory user-centred approach will be used to explore how teachers can successfully integrate sensor-based data collection and visualisation technologies into the secondary school science curriculum, and engage in Grid-enabled e-Science work across a global community. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This will involve four phases, each culminating in live trials: &lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>The first stage is working with one teacher to develop data collection/visualisation tools and class activities for a particular science curriculum area&lt;br />
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>The second and third phases&amp;nbsp;expands this to include collaboration with another UK school, and then with a non-UK school&lt;br />
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>The fourth phase is developing guidelines and supporting teachers to re-use the technologies and methods in different science curriculum areas or with different class groups.&lt;/li>
